{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_bajoran_ver01/data/sn85042243/00199918588/1923092701/0606.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE EIGHT\nSTATISTICIAN\nSEES RETURN\nOF PROSPERITY\nRoger W. Babson Believes\nDiversified Farming, Will\nHelp Northwest\nMAKING STRIDES\nCo-operative Marketing Also\na Healthy Movement to\nbe Encouraged\nMinneapolis, Minn., Sept. 27. Pros\nperity will return to the northwest\nthrough diversified farming, and co\noperative marketing, is the belief of\nRoger W. Babson, business statis\ntician.\nPointing out that this section of\nthe country was the first to he hard\nhit following the war, and believing\nit will therefore he the first to re\ncover from the business depression\nlie said:\nSound Financial Baa is\n\u201cI have kept on the track of the\ndevelopment of the diversified move\nment in this section, and I can see\nthat the farmers are making strides.\nDiversified farming will do much\ntowards placing the agricultural in\ndustry in the northwest on a sound\nlinanical basis.\u201d\nMr. Babson is in the Twin Cities\nfor a series of lectures. He believes\nthat co-operative marketing is a\nhealthy movement and snould be en\ncouraged. It teaches the farmer how\nto grow his corps and to guard\nagainsP over-production. This feature\nalone is a strong argument in favor\nof cooperative marketing, he says.\nFarming a Buaineaa\n\u2018\u2018Farming is a business,\" he says,\n\u2018\u2018and/ today farms must be operated\non a business basis if the agricul\ntural industry is to prosper. The\nfarmers who really have suffered\nduring the last two years have not\nbeen the farmers who used business\njudgment after the war in the oper\nation of their farms. There can be\noverproduction of wheat but there is\nalways a market for dairy products\nand meats. Bread is an essential\nfood, but there is a limit to the\namount we can consume. On the other\nhand, there are few limitations on\ndairy products and meats.\nMr. Babson said that through his\nobservation he has found that the\n/aimers who leased land or bought\nfarms when land was selling high\nwere the ones who were hit the hard\nest. He said that politicians have in\nmany cases greatly exaggerated the\nplight of the farmer.\nMr. Babson thinks that the man\nagement of railroads is to blame for\nconditions which exist today. He\npoints out that railroads prospered\nseveral years ago when freight rates\nwere not as high and when shipping\nand travel was much lighter.\n\u2018\u2018lt is my impression that railroad\nmanagement to a measure is to blame\nfor the apparent inability of rail\nroads to make money,\u201d he said.\nI CITY NEWS 1\n4 7*\nEllu Initiation\nThe Elks lodge plans the first fall\ninitiation on November 2. A large\nclass is expected.\nParent* of San\nMr. and Mrs. A. F! Zeigenhagel\nof Lehr are the parent* of a son\nborn at the Bismarck hospital.\nReported Improving\nP. 0. Paulson, manager of the\nBraddock Equity Exchange, who was\nseriously bruised and cut last week\nin attempting to stop a runaway\nteam driven by a small boy hauling\nwheat to his elevator is reported to\nbe in a serious condition. Mr. Paulson\nis confined to the St. Alexias hospi\ntal, having sustained severe cuts and\nbruises in addition to injuring his\nspine when he was trampled on, by\nthe horses.\nSt. Alexins Hospital\nDemetry Kostenko, Dogden,\nJames Boyle, Coleharbor, Mrs. Ed\nMagrum, Braddock, Mrs. P. J. Fox,\nUnderwood, John Roth, Fort Yates,\nMiss Margaret Fillbeck. Glen Ul\nl'in, and Mrs. Joseph Lin 7 Glen\nUllin, have entered the <St. Alexius\n\u2022hospital for treatment. F. C.\nVoight, Bismarck, F. E. Ackerman,\nRuptured?\nNon Skid Truss\nMakes You Physic\nally Fit To Do The\nHeavy Work.\no\n\\r\nCLEAN LASTING\nPerfect Fit Guaranteed.\nFINNEY\u2019S DRUG\nSTORE.\nBismarck, N. D.\nf j\nFAATDII Valley CKy H. S. PIT OFDT 00 3PNKsrn-ekUPark\nFWtMLL SkmicklM. SJU. otrl.\nWlahek. Mi** Prank Dvorak, Cen\nter, aka Charles Thorson, Glen Ul\nlin; have been discharged from the\nhe pital.\nBismarck